    <!-- ─── 1. Introduction ─── -->
    <div id="introduction" class="docs-section" style="margin-top: 2rem; padding-top: 0; border-top: none;">
        <h2 class="docs-h2">1. Introduction</h2>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Contento CMS ships with a plugin system that lets you extend content rendering, inject assets, and
            transform posts without modifying the core application. Plugins are written in plain JavaScript and
            executed on the server inside a sandboxed <strong>Jint</strong> runtime &mdash; a .NET JavaScript
            interpreter that provides a safe, isolated environment for third-party code.
        </p>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Each plugin runs in its own engine instance with strict resource limits:
        </p>
        <ul class="docs-ul">
            <li><strong>Memory:</strong> 64 MB per plugin</li>
            <li><strong>Execution timeout:</strong> 5 seconds</li>
            <li><strong>Statement cap:</strong> 100,000 statements per invocation</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Plugins can hook into post rendering, content transformation, and page lifecycle events. Per-plugin
            settings are stored as JSON in the database and injected into the runtime automatically.
        </p>
        <div class="docs-callout">
            <p>
                <strong>No network or filesystem access.</strong> Plugins cannot make HTTP requests, read files,
                or access Node.js APIs. This keeps the host application secure even when running untrusted code.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ─── 2. Plugin Structure ─── -->
    <div id="plugin-structure" class="docs-section">
        <h2 class="docs-h2">2. Plugin Structure</h2>
        <p class="docs-p">
            A plugin lives in a directory under <span class="docs-code-inline">plugins/</span>. Only the entry
            point file is required; the manifest is optional but recommended for plugins that need configurable settings.
        </p>
        <pre><code class="docs-code">plugins/
  my-plugin/
    plugin.js        # Entry point (required)
    plugin.json      # Optional manifest</code></pre>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Metadata Header</h3>
        <p class="docs-p">
            The <span class="docs-code-inline">plugin.js</span> file must begin with comment-based metadata.
            Contento parses these comments to register the plugin in the admin panel and determine which hooks
            to wire up.
        </p>
        <pre><code class="docs-code">// name: "my-plugin"
// version: "1.0.0"
// description: "What this plugin does"
// author: "Your Name"
// hooks: ["post:render"]</code></pre>
        <p class="docs-p">
            The <span class="docs-code-inline">hooks</span> line is a JSON array of hook names. Only hooks
            listed here will be called for your plugin, even if your code registers additional listeners.
        </p>
    </div>

    <!-- ─── 3. The contento API ─── -->
    <div id="contento-api" class="docs-section">
        <h2 class="docs-h2">3. The <span class="docs-code-inline">contento</span> API</h2>
        <p class="docs-p">
            The global <span class="docs-code-inline">contento</span> object is the primary interface between
            your plugin and the CMS runtime. It exposes a single registration method:
        </p>
        <pre><code class="docs-code">contento.on(hookName, callback)</code></pre>
        <ul class="docs-ul">
            <li><span class="docs-code-inline">hookName</span> &mdash; a string identifying the lifecycle event (e.g. <span class="docs-code-inline">"post:render"</span>)</li>
            <li><span class="docs-code-inline">callback</span> &mdash; a function that receives a <span class="docs-code-inline">context</span> object specific to the hook type</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Always wrap your entire plugin in an <strong>IIFE</strong> (Immediately Invoked Function Expression)
            to avoid polluting the global scope:
        </p>
        <pre><code class="docs-code">(function () {
    contento.on('post:render', function (context) {
        // Your logic here
    });
})();</code></pre>
        <div class="docs-callout">
            <p>
                <strong>Why an IIFE?</strong> Each plugin runs in the same Jint engine instance per request.
                Without an IIFE, top-level <span class="docs-code-inline">var</span> declarations become
                global and can collide with variables from other plugins.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ─── 4. Available Hooks ─── -->
    <div id="available-hooks" class="docs-section">
        <h2 class="docs-h2">4. Available Hooks</h2>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Contento fires hooks at specific points in the content lifecycle. Each hook provides a different
            <span class="docs-code-inline">context</span> object to the callback.
        </p>

        <!-- post:render -->
        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
            <span class="docs-badge">post:render</span>
        </h3>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Fired when a post is rendered for display. This is the most commonly used hook and is ideal for
            injecting UI elements (table of contents, reading time indicators, related-post cards) into the
            rendered output.
        </p>
        <p class="docs-p">Context object:</p>
        <pre><code class="docs-code">{
  post: {
    title: "Post Title",
    slug: "post-title",
    excerpt: "Short description",
    url: "https://example.com/post-title",
    featuredImage: "https://...",
    coverImage: "https://...",
    author: "Author Name",
    publishedAt: "2026-01-15T10:00:00Z",
    updatedAt: "2026-01-16T12:00:00Z",
    tags: ["tag1", "tag2"],
    category: "Technology"
  },
  document: { /* DOM-like object */ },
  site: {
    name: "My Blog",
    url: "https://example.com"
  }
}</code></pre>
        <p class="docs-p">
            The <span class="docs-code-inline">post</span> property contains read-only metadata about the
            post being rendered. The <span class="docs-code-inline">document</span> property provides a
            DOM-like object you can manipulate (see <a href="#dom-manipulation" style="color: var(--color-indigo);">Section 5</a>).
            The <span class="docs-code-inline">site</span> property provides basic site-wide information.
        </p>

        <!-- post:beforeSave -->
        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
            <span class="docs-badge">post:beforeSave</span>
        </h3>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Fired before a post is persisted to the database. Use this hook for content transformation &mdash;
            for example, auto-generating slugs, sanitizing HTML, or appending canonical metadata. The context
            includes a mutable <span class="docs-code-inline">post</span> object whose changes will be saved.
        </p>

        <!-- site:head -->
        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
            <span class="docs-badge">site:head</span>
        </h3>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Inject content into the page <span class="docs-code-inline">&lt;head&gt;</span>. Use this to add
            stylesheets, meta tags, structured data (JSON-LD), or analytics snippets. The context provides a
            <span class="docs-code-inline">head</span> element you can append children to.
        </p>

        <!-- site:footer -->
        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
            <span class="docs-badge">site:footer</span>
        </h3>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Inject content before the closing <span class="docs-code-inline">&lt;/body&gt;</span> tag. Ideal
            for loading third-party scripts, chat widgets, or deferred JavaScript. The context provides a
            <span class="docs-code-inline">body</span> element you can append children to.
        </p>

        <!-- Hook summary table -->
        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 2rem;">Hook Summary</h3>
        <table class="docs-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Hook</th>
                    <th>When</th>
                    <th>Primary Use</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">post:render</span></td>
                    <td>Post displayed to visitor</td>
                    <td>DOM manipulation, UI injection</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">post:beforeSave</span></td>
                    <td>Post saved in admin</td>
                    <td>Content transformation</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">site:head</span></td>
                    <td>Page render (head)</td>
                    <td>Meta tags, stylesheets, structured data</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">site:footer</span></td>
                    <td>Page render (footer)</td>
                    <td>Scripts, analytics, widgets</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <!-- ─── 5. DOM Manipulation ─── -->
    <div id="dom-manipulation" class="docs-section">
        <h2 class="docs-h2">5. DOM Manipulation</h2>
        <p class="docs-p">
            The <span class="docs-code-inline">context.document</span> object provides a DOM-like API powered
            by Jint. It mirrors a subset of the browser's <span class="docs-code-inline">Document</span>
            interface, so if you have experience with vanilla JavaScript DOM manipulation, you will feel at home.
        </p>
        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Document Methods</h3>
        <table class="docs-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Method</th>
                    <th>Description</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">document.createElement(tag)</span></td>
                    <td>Create a new HTML element</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">document.querySelector(selector)</span></td>
                    <td>Find the first element matching a CSS selector</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">document.head</span></td>
                    <td>Access the document's <span class="docs-code-inline">&lt;head&gt;</span> element</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">document.body</span></td>
                    <td>Access the document's <span class="docs-code-inline">&lt;body&gt;</span> element</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Element Methods &amp; Properties</h3>
        <table class="docs-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>API</th>
                    <th>Description</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">element.setAttribute(name, value)</span></td>
                    <td>Set an HTML attribute</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">element.appendChild(child)</span></td>
                    <td>Append a child element</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">element.insertBefore(newNode, refNode)</span></td>
                    <td>Insert a node before a reference node</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">element.textContent</span></td>
                    <td>Get or set the text content of an element</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">element.innerHTML</span></td>
                    <td>Get or set the inner HTML markup</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">element.style.property</span></td>
                    <td>Set an inline CSS style property</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Example: Adding a Reading Time Badge</h3>
        <pre><code class="docs-code">(function () {
    contento.on('post:render', function (context) {
        var doc = context.document;
        if (!doc || !doc.body) return;

        // Estimate reading time from body text
        var text = doc.body.textContent || '';
        var words = text.split(/\s+/).length;
        var minutes = Math.ceil(words / 200);

        // Create a badge element
        var badge = doc.createElement('div');
        badge.setAttribute('class', 'reading-time');
        badge.setAttribute('aria-label', minutes + ' minute read');
        badge.textContent = minutes + ' min read';
        badge.style.fontSize = '13px';
        badge.style.color = '#6B6B6B';
        badge.style.marginBottom = '16px';

        // Insert before the first child of the article
        var article = doc.body.querySelector('article');
        if (article && article.firstChild) {
            article.insertBefore(badge, article.firstChild);
        }
    });
})();</code></pre>
    </div>

    <!-- ─── 6. Settings & Configuration ─── -->
    <div id="settings" class="docs-section">
        <h2 class="docs-h2">6. Settings &amp; Configuration</h2>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Plugin settings are stored as JSON in the database and managed through the Contento admin panel.
            When a plugin is loaded, its settings are parsed and injected into the Jint runtime as a global
            variable called <span class="docs-code-inline">PLUGIN_SETTINGS</span>.
        </p>
        <pre><code class="docs-code">// Access your plugin's settings
var apiKey = PLUGIN_SETTINGS.apiKey || '';
var maxItems = PLUGIN_SETTINGS.maxItems || 5;
var showDates = PLUGIN_SETTINGS.showDates !== false;</code></pre>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Always provide sensible defaults using the <span class="docs-code-inline">||</span> operator.
            Settings may be undefined if the admin has not configured them yet or if the setting was added
            in a newer version of the plugin.
        </p>
        <div class="docs-callout">
            <p>
                <strong>Defining settings in the manifest.</strong> If you include a
                <span class="docs-code-inline">plugin.json</span> manifest with a
                <span class="docs-code-inline">settings</span> object, Contento will auto-generate a
                settings form in the admin panel. See <a href="#manifest" style="color: var(--color-indigo);">Section 9</a>
                for the manifest schema.
            </p>
        </div>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Supported Setting Types</h3>
        <table class="docs-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Type</th>
                    <th>Rendered As</th>
                    <th>Example</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">string</span></td>
                    <td>Text input</td>
                    <td>API keys, labels, URLs</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">number</span></td>
                    <td>Number input</td>
                    <td>Limits, thresholds, counts</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">boolean</span></td>
                    <td>Toggle switch</td>
                    <td>Feature flags</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">select</span></td>
                    <td>Dropdown</td>
                    <td>Predefined options</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <!-- ─── 7. Console & Debugging ─── -->
    <div id="debugging" class="docs-section">
        <h2 class="docs-h2">7. Console &amp; Debugging</h2>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Contento exposes a <span class="docs-code-inline">console</span> object inside the sandbox with
            three logging methods. All output is routed to the server-side application log, prefixed with the
            plugin's slug for easy filtering.
        </p>
        <table class="docs-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Method</th>
                    <th>Log Level</th>
                    <th>Example Output</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">console.log(msg)</span></td>
                    <td>INFO</td>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">[my-plugin] Processing 12 headings</span></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">console.warn(msg)</span></td>
                    <td>WARNING</td>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">[my-plugin] No headings found, skipping TOC</span></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">console.error(msg)</span></td>
                    <td>ERROR</td>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">[my-plugin] document.body is null</span></td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
        <pre><code class="docs-code">(function () {
    contento.on('post:render', function (context) {
        console.log('Plugin loaded for: ' + context.post.title);

        if (!context.document) {
            console.error('No document object available');
            return;
        }

        var headings = context.document.body.getElementsByTagName('h2');
        console.log('Found ' + headings.length + ' h2 elements');

        if (headings.length === 0) {
            console.warn('No h2 headings found, nothing to do');
        }
    });
})();</code></pre>
        <div class="docs-callout">
            <p>
                <strong>Tip:</strong> In production, avoid excessive logging. Use
                <span class="docs-code-inline">console.log</span> sparingly and prefer
                <span class="docs-code-inline">console.warn</span> or
                <span class="docs-code-inline">console.error</span> for conditions that need attention.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ─── 8. Security & Sandbox ─── -->
    <div id="security" class="docs-section">
        <h2 class="docs-h2">8. Security &amp; Sandbox</h2>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Contento takes a defense-in-depth approach to plugin security. Every plugin runs inside a Jint
            interpreter with strict constraints that prevent malicious or runaway code from affecting the host system.
        </p>
        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Sandbox Constraints</h3>
        <table class="docs-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Constraint</th>
                    <th>Limit</th>
                    <th>What Happens When Exceeded</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td>Memory</td>
                    <td>64 MB per plugin</td>
                    <td>Execution terminates immediately</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Execution time</td>
                    <td>5 seconds</td>
                    <td>Execution terminates, timeout error logged</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Statement count</td>
                    <td>100,000</td>
                    <td>Execution terminates, limit error logged</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Strict mode</td>
                    <td>Always on</td>
                    <td>Syntax errors are thrown, not silently ignored</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">What Plugins Cannot Do</h3>
        <ul class="docs-ul">
            <li>Access the filesystem (no <span class="docs-code-inline">require('fs')</span>, no <span class="docs-code-inline">import</span>)</li>
            <li>Make network requests (no <span class="docs-code-inline">fetch</span>, <span class="docs-code-inline">XMLHttpRequest</span>, or <span class="docs-code-inline">require('http')</span>)</li>
            <li>Access Node.js built-in modules</li>
            <li>Spawn processes or child threads</li>
            <li>Access environment variables or system properties</li>
            <li>Modify the Jint engine configuration</li>
            <li>Access or interfere with other plugins' state</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Isolation Model</h3>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Each plugin runs in its own isolated Jint engine. This means that global variables defined in one
            plugin are not visible to any other plugin. If a plugin crashes or times out, other plugins continue
            to execute normally.
        </p>
    </div>

    <!-- ─── 9. Plugin Manifest ─── -->
    <div id="manifest" class="docs-section">
        <h2 class="docs-h2">9. Plugin Manifest (plugin.json)</h2>
        <p class="docs-p">
            The manifest is an optional JSON file that provides structured metadata about your plugin. While the
            comment-based metadata in <span class="docs-code-inline">plugin.js</span> covers the basics, the
            manifest unlocks additional features like auto-generated settings forms and declared permissions.
        </p>
        <pre><code class="docs-code">{
  "name": "My Plugin",
  "slug": "my-plugin",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "author": "Your Name",
  "description": "What this plugin does",
  "entryPoint": "plugin.js",
  "permissions": [],
  "hooks": ["post:render"],
  "settings": {
    "apiKey": {
      "type": "string",
      "label": "API Key"
    },
    "maxItems": {
      "type": "number",
      "default": 5
    }
  }
}</code></pre>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Manifest Fields</h3>
        <table class="docs-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Field</th>
                    <th>Required</th>
                    <th>Description</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">name</span></td>
                    <td>Yes</td>
                    <td>Human-readable plugin name</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">slug</span></td>
                    <td>Yes</td>
                    <td>URL-safe identifier (lowercase, hyphens only)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">version</span></td>
                    <td>Yes</td>
                    <td>Semantic version (e.g. <span class="docs-code-inline">1.0.0</span>)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">author</span></td>
                    <td>No</td>
                    <td>Plugin author name</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">description</span></td>
                    <td>No</td>
                    <td>Brief description shown in admin panel</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">entryPoint</span></td>
                    <td>No</td>
                    <td>Entry file path (defaults to <span class="docs-code-inline">plugin.js</span>)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">permissions</span></td>
                    <td>No</td>
                    <td>Reserved for future permission system</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">hooks</span></td>
                    <td>Yes</td>
                    <td>Array of hook names this plugin uses</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><span class="docs-code-inline">settings</span></td>
                    <td>No</td>
                    <td>Settings schema for auto-generated admin form</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Settings Schema</h3>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Each key in the <span class="docs-code-inline">settings</span> object becomes a configurable field
            in the admin panel. The key name is what you access via
            <span class="docs-code-inline">PLUGIN_SETTINGS</span> at runtime.
        </p>
        <pre><code class="docs-code">"settings": {
  "heading": {
    "type": "string",
    "label": "Section Heading",
    "default": "On this page"
  },
  "minHeadings": {
    "type": "number",
    "label": "Minimum headings to show TOC",
    "default": 2
  },
  "includeH3": {
    "type": "boolean",
    "label": "Include H3 headings",
    "default": true
  },
  "position": {
    "type": "select",
    "label": "TOC Position",
    "options": ["top", "sidebar"],
    "default": "top"
  }
}</code></pre>
    </div>

    <!-- ─── 10. Complete Example ─── -->
    <div id="example" class="docs-section">
        <h2 class="docs-h2">10. Complete Example: Table of Contents Plugin</h2>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Let's build a real plugin from scratch. This plugin scans the rendered post for
            <span class="docs-code-inline">h2</span> and <span class="docs-code-inline">h3</span> headings,
            generates anchor IDs for each one, and injects a styled table of contents at the top of the article.
        </p>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Step 1: Create the Plugin Directory</h3>
        <pre><code class="docs-code">plugins/
  table-of-contents/
    plugin.js
    plugin.json</code></pre>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Step 2: Write the Manifest</h3>
        <p class="docs-p">
            The manifest declares the plugin's metadata and its configurable settings:
        </p>
        <pre><code class="docs-code">{
  "name": "Table of Contents",
  "slug": "table-of-contents",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "author": "Contento",
  "description": "Generates a table of contents from h2/h3 headings in post content.",
  "entryPoint": "plugin.js",
  "hooks": ["post:render"],
  "settings": {
    "heading": {
      "type": "string",
      "label": "TOC Heading",
      "default": "On this page"
    },
    "minHeadings": {
      "type": "number",
      "label": "Minimum headings required",
      "default": 2
    }
  }
}</code></pre>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Step 3: Write the Plugin Code</h3>
        <p class="docs-p">
            The full <span class="docs-code-inline">plugin.js</span> implementation:
        </p>
        <pre><code class="docs-code">// name: "table-of-contents"
// version: "1.0.0"
// description: "Generates a table of contents from h2/h3 headings in post content."
// author: "Contento"
// hooks: ["post:render"]

(function () {
    contento.on('post:render', function (context) {
        var doc = context.document;
        if (!doc) return;

        var body = doc.body;
        if (!body) return;

        // Find all h2 and h3 elements
        var headings = [];
        var allElements = body.getElementsByTagName('*');
        for (var i = 0; i &lt; allElements.length; i++) {
            var el = allElements[i];
            var tag = el.tagName ? el.tagName.toLowerCase() : '';
            if (tag === 'h2' || tag === 'h3') {
                var text = el.textContent || '';
                var id = text.toLowerCase()
                    .replace(/[^a-z0-9]+/g, '-')
                    .replace(/^-|-$/g, '');
                el.setAttribute('id', id);
                headings.push({ tag: tag, text: text, id: id });
            }
        }

        // Read settings with defaults
        var minHeadings = (PLUGIN_SETTINGS &amp;&amp; PLUGIN_SETTINGS.minHeadings) || 2;
        var tocHeading = (PLUGIN_SETTINGS &amp;&amp; PLUGIN_SETTINGS.heading) || 'On this page';

        if (headings.length &lt; minHeadings) return;

        // Build TOC HTML
        var tocHtml = '&lt;nav class="toc" style="'
            + 'background:#f8f8f6;'
            + 'border:1px solid #e5e5e3;'
            + 'border-radius:8px;'
            + 'padding:16px 20px;'
            + 'margin-bottom:24px;"&gt;';
        tocHtml += '&lt;strong style="font-size:14px;"&gt;'
            + tocHeading + '&lt;/strong&gt;';
        tocHtml += '&lt;ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;margin:8px 0 0;"&gt;';

        for (var j = 0; j &lt; headings.length; j++) {
            var h = headings[j];
            var indent = h.tag === 'h3' ? 'padding-left:16px;' : '';
            tocHtml += '&lt;li style="margin:4px 0;' + indent + '"&gt;';
            tocHtml += '&lt;a href="#' + h.id + '" style="'
                + 'color:#3D5A80;'
                + 'font-size:13px;'
                + 'text-decoration:none;"&gt;'
                + h.text + '&lt;/a&gt;';
            tocHtml += '&lt;/li&gt;';
        }
        tocHtml += '&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/nav&gt;';

        // Insert TOC before the first heading or at
        // the start of the article
        var container = doc.createElement('div');
        container.innerHTML = tocHtml;
        var article = body.querySelector('article') || body;
        if (article.firstChild) {
            article.insertBefore(container, article.firstChild);
        } else {
            article.appendChild(container);
        }
    });
})();</code></pre>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Step 4: Install &amp; Test</h3>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Upload the plugin through the Contento admin panel under
            <strong>Plugins</strong>. Once enabled, visit any post with two or more headings and you
            will see the table of contents rendered at the top of the article body.
        </p>
        <p class="docs-p">
            Use the admin's plugin settings page to customize the TOC heading text and the minimum number
            of headings required before the TOC appears.
        </p>
    </div>

    <!-- ─── 11. Best Practices ─── -->
    <div id="best-practices" class="docs-section">
        <h2 class="docs-h2">11. Best Practices</h2>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1rem;">Defensive Coding</h3>
        <ul class="docs-ul">
            <li>Always check for <span class="docs-code-inline">null</span> and <span class="docs-code-inline">undefined</span> before accessing context properties</li>
            <li>Return early instead of throwing exceptions &mdash; a thrown error terminates only your plugin, but clean early returns are more predictable</li>
            <li>Use default values for all settings with the <span class="docs-code-inline">||</span> operator</li>
        </ul>
        <pre><code class="docs-code">// Good: defensive checks
var doc = context.document;
if (!doc || !doc.body) return;

var title = context.post ? context.post.title : 'Untitled';
var maxItems = PLUGIN_SETTINGS.maxItems || 5;</code></pre>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Scope Isolation</h3>
        <ul class="docs-ul">
            <li>Always wrap your plugin in an IIFE</li>
            <li>Use <span class="docs-code-inline">var</span> instead of undeclared assignments to avoid implicit globals</li>
            <li>Never modify the <span class="docs-code-inline">contento</span> object or <span class="docs-code-inline">PLUGIN_SETTINGS</span></li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Performance</h3>
        <ul class="docs-ul">
            <li>Keep DOM operations minimal &mdash; batch reads and writes where possible</li>
            <li>Avoid deep recursive traversal of the DOM tree</li>
            <li>Use <span class="docs-code-inline">querySelector</span> over manual tree walking when possible</li>
            <li>Be mindful of the 100,000 statement limit; large string concatenation loops can approach it</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Accessibility</h3>
        <ul class="docs-ul">
            <li>Use semantic HTML elements (<span class="docs-code-inline">&lt;nav&gt;</span>, <span class="docs-code-inline">&lt;aside&gt;</span>, <span class="docs-code-inline">&lt;section&gt;</span>) instead of generic <span class="docs-code-inline">&lt;div&gt;</span> where appropriate</li>
            <li>Add <span class="docs-code-inline">aria-label</span> attributes to interactive and landmark elements</li>
            <li>Ensure injected content has sufficient color contrast</li>
            <li>Do not remove or override existing ARIA attributes in the document</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="docs-h3" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Compatibility</h3>
        <ul class="docs-ul">
            <li>Test your plugin with both light and dark mode themes</li>
            <li>Use CSS custom properties (e.g. <span class="docs-code-inline">var(--color-ink)</span>) in inline styles where possible so that injected content adapts to the active theme</li>
            <li>Avoid hardcoded widths &mdash; use relative units and <span class="docs-code-inline">max-width</span> for responsive layouts</li>
            <li>Do not assume a specific post structure; always check before manipulating</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

